:INFO [align:center]
Slatesource in the Open
This is the workshop, not the showroom. Every release, every decision and \
every rough edge of building a publishing platform, written down as it \
happens. The work is the thing worth showing.

:DURATION
2023-05-11T00:00:00Z
2026-07-19T00:00:00Z

:INFO
Since the First Commit
The first commit landed on 11 May 2023 and said, in full, "Initial commit". \
Everything after it was built in evenings and weekends, one problem at a time.

:STATS
[icon:CHART] Commits | 1,801
[icon:CLOCK] In the making | 3 years, 2 months
[icon:BOLT] Backend files | 866
[icon:BOLT] Frontend files | 700
[icon:CHECK] Chip types shipped | 29 of 43

:INFO
The Long Way Round
None of this was built in a sprint. The chip system moved to a unified data \
model in April 2024, more than a year before most of the chips that use it \
existed. The chext parser moved server-side in March 2026, two years after \
the first slate rendered. Foundations first, features after. Slower, and it \
holds up better.

:TIMELINE
The Arc So Far
2023-05-11 | First commit
2024-01 | Infrastructure hardening, CDN and pipelines
2024-04 | Chips migrated to one data model
2024-06 | Frontend moved to Vite
2024-09 | R1, the first stable release
2025-04 | Creator Collective opens
2025-06 | Grid layout overhaul, half and full
2026-02 | GitHub integration, slates sync from a repo
2026-03 | Chext parser moves server-side
2026-07 | 43 chip types in the vocabulary

:INFO
What a Slate Can Hold
Forty-three chip types exist as a vocabulary. Twenty-nine of them can be \
written today from a plain text file in a Git repository. The feature pages \
take one part each and open it up properly: what it does, how it behaves in \
use, and where the design went sideways before it settled.

:PATH
Changelog
Releases and improvements, close to per commit, going back to January 2024.

:PATH
Roadmap
What is planned and roughly in what order. Subject to change, and it changes.

:PATH
Wishlist
Ideas on the radar and not yet committed to. Several entries here have since \
shipped, which is the honest way to read a wishlist.

:INFO
The Feature Pages
Twenty pages, one per feature, each documenting a working part of the \
platform in depth. Where a feature can demonstrate itself, it does. The \
Shader page runs a live shader. The Poll page carries a real poll. The Map \
page drops a real pin. The Code page renders real code.

:QUOTE [quotetype:PLAIN]
The details of the work are the flex. Three years of evenings deserves an \
artifact that shows it.

:NOTE
This slate is maintained as code and syncs on every push. Nothing here is \
staged for an audience, which is rather the point of keeping it in the open.

